  "text": "The formula evaluation chain in LibreOffice Calc Spreadsheet Engine (sc/) follows this process:\n\n1. **Formula Parsing (sc/source/core/tool/compiler.cxx - ScCompiler class)**: When a user enters a formula like `=SUM(A1:A10)`, the ScCompiler tokenizer parses the formula string character by character, identifying tokens (function names, operators, cell references, literals). The compiler uses a state machine (ssGetChar, ssGetValue, ssGetIdent, ssGetReference states defined around line 90-100 of compiler.cxx) to process the formula.\n\n2. **Token Array Creation (include/formula/tokenarray.hxx - FormulaTokenArray class, line 234)**: The parsed tokens are stored in a FormulaTokenArray with two representations:\n   - pCode: Normal token order\n   - pRPN: Reverse Polish Notation for efficient stack-based evaluation\n   The token array also stores ScRecalcMode flags (line 242) indicating when the formula needs recalculation.\n\n3. **Formula Cell Storage (sc/inc/formulacell.hxx - ScFormulaCell class, line 120)**: Each formula cell is an instance of ScFormulaCell, which:\n   - Holds a pointer to the ScTokenArray (pCode at line 147)\n   - Maintains flags for dirty state (bDirty at line 124) and compilation (bCompile at line 128)\n   - Stores the calculated result (aResult at line 143)\n   - Tracks cell group membership for grouped formula evaluation (mxGroup at line 123)\n\n4. **Recalculation Triggering**: When a cell or its dependencies change, the cell is marked dirty. The ScRecalcMode enum (include/formula/tokenarray.hxx, line 59) determines recalculation priorities:\n   - ALWAYS: Always recalculate (volatile functions like NOW())\n   - ONLOAD_MUST: Recalculate after document load\n   - ONLOAD_ONCE: One-time recalculation after import\n   - ONLOAD_LENIENT: Lenient recalculation (external links)\n   - NORMAL: Standard recalculation on dependency changes\n   - FORCED: Force recalculation (for macros with side effects)\n   - ONREFMOVE: Recalculate when reference moves\n\n5. **Formula Interpretation (sc/source/core/data/formulacell.cxx - ScFormulaCell::Interpret() at line 1500)**: When a dirty formula cell is encountered, Interpret() is called. This method:\n   - Checks for circular references and recursion limits\n   - Creates a ScInterpreter instance with the formula's token array\n   - Calls ScInterpreter::Interpret() to evaluate the formula\n   - Returns the calculated result\n\n6. **Bytecode Evaluation (sc/source/core/inc/interpre.hxx - ScInterpreter class, defined at line 197)**: The ScInterpreter is the core evaluation engine:\n   - Header defined in sc/source/core/inc/interpre.hxx\n   - Constructor at line 1126 initializes the interpreter with a formula cell, document, token array, and position\n   - Main evaluation method: `formula::StackVar Interpret()` at line 1138 returns the result type\n   - Implementation split across 8 files (interpr1.cxx through interpr8.cxx in sc/source/core/tool/) for manageability\n   - Uses a stack-based architecture to evaluate RPN tokens\n   - Individual function methods (ScSum, ScAverage, ScCount, etc.) implement specific operations\n\n7. **Function Implementation Examples** (sc/source/core/tool/interpr1.cxx and others):\n   - SUM function: Iterates through range, accumulates numeric values\n   - Each function validates parameter counts and types\n   - Returns results by pushing values onto the interpreter stack\n\n**Key Architecture Points**:\n- The token array uses RPN internally for efficient stack-based evaluation\n- ScInterpreter maintains a formula stack (ScTokenStack, line 151-155 in interpre.hxx) for intermediate results\n- Matrix formulas and array operations are supported through matrix token references\n- Grouped formula evaluation allows vectorized computation for performance\n- The interpreter context (ScInterpreterContext) manages caches and per-evaluation state\n- Error handling through FormulaError enum tracks calculation errors (division by zero, circular references, etc.)\n\nThis design separates concerns: compilation (ScCompiler) handles parsing, storage (FormulaTokenArray) holds the compiled form, and interpretation (ScInterpreter) executes the formula. The recalculation scheduler (ScRecalcMode) determines which cells need evaluation when dependencies change."
}

